scenario: multinational negotiations for repurposing waste for energy, fashion, manufacturing and fertiliser started.
the global acknowledgement of overfishing and the ratification of science-based targets is an accepted global framework are agreed at cop in singapore.
coca (cities of climate action) agree on planet first as a guiding principle above all else at their annual meeting at the virtual planet meeting room, no physical travel was necessary.

the parliament of the commons was established as an arm of the united nations (un) general assembly bringing voices of the global commons, like our oceans, forests, savannahs and atmosphere, to the world stage for the first time; each has their own flag flying at the un. talks about giving ai a voice started in the 2040s and proved controversial. a healthy debate is ongoing.

the climate march was held in response to food and biofuel price hikes. although devastating, these events heightened the global debate on how to sustainably feed the growing population and ultimately catalysed action.
what was once known as rubbish or garbage is one of today’s most valuable ecology and is mined both on land and sea.
deaths from non-infectious and non-communicable diseases will account for over 75 percent of annual deaths.
the annual number of deaths from cancer will increase globally around 60 percent.
cardiovascular disease deaths are expected to increase to 23.4 million.
the following diseases are expected to be the leading cause of death: coronary artery disease, cerebrovascular diseases and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (copd).
copd is mainly attributed to the projected increase in tobacco use. in comparison, road accidents would be the fifth leading cause of death.
the growing use of vehicles combined with economic growth in countries with low and middle average incomes leads to high road fatalities.
the proportion of the world's population living in cities will increased from 52 percent in 2011 to 60 percent.
the population of urban areas in less developed countries increased from 2.67 billion in 2011 to 3.92 billion.
almost all of the world's population growth of an estimated 1.3 billion people will be concentrated in urban areas.
more and more people will live in cities.
the city life is expected to consist mainly of one-person households in germany.
one-person households increased from 40 percent in 2009 to 43 percent.
the development of two-person households share is estimated at 38 percent.
the proportion of families, the main group of households with three or more people, fell below ten percent.
the annual carbon dioxide emissions, which increased by 40 percent since 1990, led to acidification of the oceans.
the carbon dioxide emissions and other anthropogenic greenhouse gases led to further progressive global warming of the climate.
the air temperature increases by an annual mean of 0.5°c.
the precipitation in summer decreased by around 15 percent, while in winter it increases by up to ten percent.
a further increase in carbon dioxide emissions is triggered by the rising global energy demand.
human interventions in the biosphere led to the loss of biological diversity.
in view of the global population growth and in background of climate change, global food security is viewed as a difficult global challenge.
more than 500 million people in less developed countries suffer from malnutrition.
around 1.1 billion people have no access to clean drinking water.
around 2.6 billion people lack access to basic sanitation.
almost half of the world's population live in regions where water is scarce.
the world is moving towards a global knowledge society.
new key data in research and development (r&d) around the world supports the view on global r&d expenditure and on new forms of global cooperation.
the driver of r&d development is the widespread use of information and communication technologies and the digitization of information.
digitization globally expands education.
the global educational landscape was shaped through the upswing of the knowledge economy.
the explosive expansion of higher education around the world reshaped the education.
an increasing number of people are able to develop new educational opportunities, so that the global supply of highly qualified people increased significantly.

due to the advancing use of technical innovations and the increasing digital character of culture, media literacy is the most important skill for unrestricted participation in society and employability.
service innovations play an important role in promoting participation.
further innovations for the more intuitive operation of new devices and services help to alleviate the digital competence pressure.
lifelong learning is a basic requirement for the information and knowledge society.
digital media offer effective possibilities here, but require a further, cognitive-neuroscientific and didactic investigation with regard to the possible negative impact on people.
the integration of digital technologies in every area of life arouses fears among many citizens, differences in access to information and in the use of the available information must be discussed.

the transfer and acquisition of knowledge have changed due to the continuously increasing use of computers and the internet, in addition to the increasing digital competence pressure, the effects of computer use on individual and social development are being discussed.
knowledge and information are available everywhere in the form of large amounts of data due to digitization.
knowledge that a person had to learn and retain decades ago can now be stored digitally and called up at short notice and almost anywhere, many learning processes have changed as a result.
to mention the active learning and memorizing of telephone numbers, have become almost superfluous.
the outsourcing of thinking about machines exposes citizens to increased digital competence pressure.
controversial debates about the effects of outsourcing knowledge and thinking on human development are unsettling society.
the extreme position that due to the increased use of digital media, people's intellectual performance is reduced, combined with the requirement to limit media consumption to a necessary minimum.
media didactics claim that media use stimulates creativity, stimulates thinking and has, among other things, positive neurological effects.
the decoupling of the world of learning and living from digital media is no longer possible.
the growing shortage of skilled workers and the falling half-life of specialist knowledge poses a societal design task.
the canon of education and skills was be re-designed since knowledge that previously had to be learned can now be easily researched.
in addition to public participation to formulate and advise on research agendas, citizens are doing research on their own.
the focus of citizen research is weather research, biology, health, nature and environmental protection, but also archeology, cryptology, information science, amateur drones and space research.
the decentralized of knowledge production poses a challenge for society and the scientific system.
citizen research is able to solve societal tasks, such as the preservation of biodiversity or the deciphering of protein folds.
citizen research in biohacking poses a danger in the field of genetic manipulation by amateurs.
the us and uk are pioneers in citizen research.
drivers and dynamics of citizen research are mostly curiosity, or as a meaningful activity and form of social participation.
citizen research evolves through powerful information and communication technology, open access, cheaper laboratory equipment and new measuring devices or apps for smartphones.
crowdfunding increases and enables citizen research.
there is an increase in use of 3d printers in the private sector and research activities in civil society.
governments and companies support citizens' research in some cases in order to increase the legitimacy and acceptance of research and innovation.
the focus of citizen research programs are societal challenges and the increasing opening of in-house innovation.
due to the complexity of the scientific system and the often tense relationship between established researchers and citizen researchers, citizen research faces challenges.
german research institutions are increasingly having to deal with new participation requirements, especially at the eu level.
there is a lack of processes and routines for the legitimate and effective integration of citizens into research practice.
the independence of citizen research harbors dangers: genetic manipulation by amateurs, biohacking, can contribute to the uncontrolled entry of genetically modified organisms into the environment.
the blurring line between non-scientifically qualified citizens with research ambitions and scientists is referred to as the “scientification of society” and the “democratization of science”.
the need for society and research to learn from one another is increasingly recognized, but the implementation is still pending.
the igem49 initiative with its competitions, are pioneers in the initiation and implementation of citizen research.
the contract between science and society is changing, resulting in completely new concepts of research policy to use the opportunities of citizen research and to manage their risks.
an excellent research environment includes easy and inexpensive access to scientific knowledge.
young scientists are financially heavily burdened by the common practice of having research work published by private publishers.
university and research institute libraries suffer from the cost burden of journal subscriptions.
society increasingly demands free access to knowledge financed by taxpayers' money.
open access, free access to scientific knowledge such as primary data or scientific literature enable free access to knowledge.

the berlin declaration on open access to scientific knowledge is adopted by 19 international research organizations and has been signed by a total of 363 national and international research institutions.
the initiators are in favor of publishing publicly financed scientific papers free of charge instead of having them published exclusively by publishers.
they call for the complete revision of the previous scientific publication structures.
knowledge that was previously financed by the general public is now re-financed by the public purse.
all citizens can use scientific publications via the internet in every conceivable, legal way.
the prescribed publication via open access has a far-reaching encroachment on the freedom of the press and publication as well as the freedoms of the author.
open access has been taken up at the level of the european union, but there is still an urgent need for clarification regarding the design of global implementation.

the handling of open access authors' copyrights, the technical implementation options, the necessary quality assurance as well as the possible publication and financing structures still need regulations.

the different financing models for open access have a more precise consideration, as they equally affect the authors, scientific institutions and the scientific publishers involved in the publication.
it is particularly important to explore the opportunities, but also the risks, of the various open access publication models.
research is fast, simple and inexpensive: free access to the latest scientific publications is essential for all research and innovation efforts.
improving access to knowledge in the fields of education, science, culture and the media shows positive effects on innovation.
much of the public research is funded by society, since the knowledge society is an essential basis of economic and social coexistence.
free and real-time access to the research results financed in this way is therefore seen by many stakeholders as a logical step.
university budgets are falling further and pressure from society increases, and good higher education in the us is more expensive then ever.
at us american state universities, a bachelor's degree often costs more than $ 35,000 in fees, tuition fees for training at a research university now often exceed the capabilities of many families.
there is a great unmet need for higher education, the situation is currently intensifying the development of online universities as a growth market.
the development of online universities is a growing market in which commercial players are repositioning themselves.
start-up companies such as coursera or udacity that offer online lectures are attracting attention more than ever.
informal education manages to collect substantial venture capital and enter into collaborations with well-known universities.
unofficial education institutes have access to more than 100,000 online students for individual lecturing sessions.
bertelsmann is investing a double-digit million amount in a virtual university.
due to the range of online offers, the university landscape changed significantly globally.
in germany, the cost of university entrance is still much lower than in the usa.
students learn from the best professionals in the world, such as nobel prize winners or successful entrepreneurs, via distance learning.
virtualization fundamentally changed the entry requirements for higher education, while globalization established university branches abroad.
the disruptive potential of online universities could develop further because students in social networks are already discussing and archiving questions and answers online.
obstacles of distance learning are the dangers of cheating in exams as well as the adequate consideration of academic achievements.
universities still are part of the innovation system.

the traditional model of research and teaching at universities has been remodeled fundamentally: exams are open-book, virtuality is the new normal and buildings are only needed for in-person collaboration.
universities are a central element in the knowledge society, a profound change in higher education also has far-reaching effects on the knowledge society.
simplified forms of access and reduced costs through online universities or other forms of digitization in education increased participation in the knowledge society globally.
new starting points for easier access to higher education in germany improved the quality of study.
knowledge and knowledge transfer opened up research contributions from science for the economy and provides impulses for the direction of science.
the need to promote knowledge transfer is undisputed: intensive efforts to improve knowledge transfer are a goal in germany as well as in japan, the usa and the rest of europe.
countries such as china, taiwan, india, singapore and south korea are relying on open knowledge transfer.
the main focus of open knowledge transfer is to make the knowledge generated in universities usable for the achievement of social goals.
sectors of the higher education landscape in which knowledge transfer is successful are experiencing a change in academic culture: they dedicate themselves to the achievement of social goals.

due to the increasing transfer activities at universities, a change in the role identity of university researchers can be observed: in addition to the academic core identity, there is now a secondary economic identity in individual cases.

a long-standing debate in the usa about how to deal with possible conflicts of interest in research, which is particularly intense in medical research arises: shall they freely publish all medical research?
companies use academic knowledge as a source leading to them making their own scientific contributions and publishing them in academic discourse.
the publication frequency of scientists with industrial support is twice as high as that of other scientists.
studies show that academic inventors publish better scientific articles than their non-patenting counterparts.
cooperation projects generate academically valuable insights and ideas. the projects are application-oriented and do not lead directly to results that can be published.
the increase in knowledge transfer can itself change the type and scope of scientific exchange and thus the academic culture in institutes with a high rate of third-party funding.
it is regarded as an open question what relevance, size and impact the increase in knowledge transfer has on which fields of research and innovation.
the efforts to transfer scientific knowledge into socially desirable applications underscores the importance of sufficient basic public funding for free basic research.
a dominant dependence on third-party funding led to a change in the academic culture in the institutes concerned, which impacted the knowledge production itself.
social innovations are regulations, activities and procedures that deviate from the usual pattern and have societal consequences and contribute more sustainably to solving social problems.
social innovations are increasingly made by citizens, civil society organizations and politics and are seen as contribution to increasing the quality of life and overcoming structural challenges.
social innovations are being developed within applicable innovation research concepts, in order to be able to use the potentials more systematically.
the shift towards more attention to social innovations goes hand in hand with an increasing political orientation towards social needs.
the range of tasks of civil society organizations is broadening and work with or on people is becoming more knowledge-based and professional.
the integration of common values ​​in companies and philanthropic projects gained importance.
civil society organizations such as the german red cross are increasingly expressing the need to optimize their processes through scientific support.
social innovations represent a key to addressing societal needs.
obstacles to social innovations are the diversity of social practices and the lack of awareness of innovation potential.
there is no uniform understanding of social innovations, their conditions and consequences, their dynamics are relatively unclear.
a close interlinking of social and technical innovations increase the potential for solutions for society as a whole.
problems such as mass unemployment, the erosion of social security systems and the aggravation ecological risks will not be manageable without the implementation of social innovations.
little is known about the differences between social innovations and technical innovations, as well as the benefits and costs of implementation and necessary adjustments in the environment.

the integration of social innovations requires additional skills such as a holistic understanding of individual and collective needs and the practices to meet them, as well as creativity, willingness to learn and trust.
the systematic analysis and targeted raising of social innovation potential is very promising. social innovations complement, trigger or even replace technical innovations.
discrimination against women in large parts of the world is still evident.

discrimination against women is reflected in poorer educational opportunities, more difficult access to certain areas of the working world and high hurdles for assuming political offices and mandates.

current studies show that the life chances of women, especially in developing and emerging countries, are beginning to improve significantly in many areas of life, while the relationships between the sexes are developing.
38% of all small businesses are run by women.
women in developing countries make up 17% of the industrial workforce and 24% of those employed in the service sector.
worldwide, women represent 40% of employees, 43% of agricultural workers and - for the first time in history - more than half of the student body.
attendance at tertiary education by women has increased sevenfold since 1970.
more girls attend secondary school than boys.
women are increasingly fighting for personal and economic freedom, especially in developing countries, they often act as drivers for fundamental positive changes in political.
gender relations for the global society of the future are less researched and present in the public consciousness than technological or economic trend disruptions.
women in developing countries increasingly cultivate their own agricultural land or migrate to metropolitan areas far away from their place of birth in order to work in export-oriented companies.

working conditions and wages in developing countries are often poor, but for women, employment is still financial independence, autonomy, an increasing level of information and education as well as the expansion of your networks beyond family ties.

the economy and the desire for freedom of women results in significant social cascade effects: as a population average, women make greater use of opportunities for advancement through education and convey this attitude to their children.
woman in developing countries pay more attention than average to initiatives on health, family planning and environmental protection because their workforce depends on them.
by advocating for genderneutral property rights, the risks of lower agricultural investment was reduced.
women in developing countries take out the majority of micro loans and reinvest savings in their small businesses.
women in developing countries use it technology to expand their social radius beyond patriarchal control.

women in developing countries join together to form networks and cooperatives or invest in their communities in order to base their progress on an economically, socially and ecologically sustainable basis.
the societies in developing and emerging countries react to the emancipation of women highly positively.
women in developing countries are the main change agents and pioneers in key areas.
a reduction in working hours, as demanded by trade unions and employee associations, is now often practiced because of economic crisis situations.
many employees experience a reduction in working hours as increasingly contrary to their actual needs.
the need for more time sovereignty, i.e. for the individual to determine how time is used, is growing.
the reasons for more time sovereignty in employment are to be found in the intensification of work, the difficult work-life balance and the low increase in wages.
drivers and dynamics are more time sovereignty in employment, the need for ways to combine family, leisure time and work is the driver for the need for more time sovereignty.
for 69% of the population and 78% of parents, improving the compatibility of family and work is one of the urgent political tasks.
starting a family influences the employment behavior of employees more than ever.
a high rate of mothers limit their ability to work up to the age of 30 and only reach the highest employment rate at the age of around 49.
childfree women or women who later enter the active family phase have the highest employment rate in the younger years.
there is a growing desire among men to deal more intensively with the family, even in the early stages of working life.
valuing family and time of employees are moving more and more into the focus of working environments’ interests.
everyday life and individual lifestyle drives employees for a more effective and flexible division of working hours.
flexible working hours, shorter work in the family phases, flexible retirement as well as the opportunity to take educational offers are an integral part of every career.
the increasing competitive pressure and measures to balance work and private life are an investment in the workforce of the company, motivates employers to deregulate working hours.
existing working time models and statutory regulations, such as the part-time act, are adapted to the constant change in the world of work.
the impending shortage of skilled workers and the effects of demographic changes are considered with regard to future working time models.
business management requirements and binding framework conditions enable flexibility for the mutual benefit of employer and employee.
there is a need for new working time models that take into account the social, economic and ecological consequences.
a life phase-oriented employment biography is taken into account as design options for the individual working environment.
the demand for technologies that support the flexibilization of working hours increases heavily.
the further development of mobile devices, faster internet connections and cloud computing increased the independence of location and thus time sovereignty of work.
education at a later stage in life is encouraged. the use of employees even after the statutory retirement age mitigates the effects of demographic change.
lifelong learning reached a peak, since the employee can design his or her work biography individually.
the issue of time sovereignty reached a peak: it affects both the economy and every individual citizen.
the classic nuclear family, consisting of father, mother and one or more children, will continue to lose importance.
nuclear families are increasingly being replaced by alternative, more complex, but also more unstable forms of life.
in addition to the traditional family, there are, for example, living communities with children or single parents. new, family-like ways of life are increasingly shaping the image of society.

forms of life such as non-marital partnerships, childless marriages, partnerships with separated households, multi-generational partnerships, same-sex couples with children or non-exclusive forms of relationships increased significantly.

the effects of the social pluralization of family-like ways of life not only offer opportunities, but also face great challenges. the main thing to clarify is how the social infrastructures are to be adapted to the new ways of life and what suitable legal framework conditions can be created for the children living in alternative partnerships.
the nuclear family is still the most common form of coexistence in germany, but the proportion of alternative family forms are on the rise.
changed framework conditions in modern society, the equalization of educational opportunities for men and women, reforms of family law, enable the emergence of alternative life concepts.
change in social values, the increased individualization and growing economic uncertainties, enable the emergence of alternative life concepts, such as family-like ways of life.
every fourth child lives with just one parent or in a stepfamily.
biotechnological processes or methods of reproductive medicine can, for example, put the smallest unit of previous family forms, the mother-child unit, into perspective.
the increasing trend towards new forms of biotechnological development for families led to numerous requirements and needs, especially in the infrastructural area.
innovations are required in terms of both technical and social infrastructure in order to be able to adequately meet the changed requirements of modern family constellations.
the high degree of mobility and flexibility required in today's knowledge society in both private and professional life can only be met with difficulty by families with children.
the increasing proportion of working mothers additionally intensifies the need for unlimited mobility.
home workplaces and modern information and communication technologies, but also good childcare options, can take the strain off parents.
the demographic shift towards an aging society is putting the prevailing cultural youth paradigm to the test.
international surveys show that a majority of the population of all ages share the view, that the youth craze in society is too pronounced.
the youth craze is replaced by ideals and values ​​that better correspond to the self-image of people over 50.
in germany and most industrialized countries, market research finds that children and young people are not only in the minority in terms of number, but also in terms of purchasing power.
in germany, young people lost resonance in market and in the media, their relevance for the social self-image decreases.
advertising and marketing is more geared towards best agers and is stylized into a new “lead milieu” of consumption.
youthfulness continues to be an important value for best agers, but now surrounds ideas such as life experience, comfort, enjoyment and quality standards.

youthfulness surrounds ideas such as stability and security and depth of experience, but also an interest in civic engagement to create new models of “active non-retirement” and no longer only appearance.
market researchers use the data from best agers to find consumer trends in areas such as health and wellness, personal care and cosmetics, travel and recreation, nutrition and gastronomy.
in industries such as household items, watches and jewelry, women's clothing, pharmaceuticals and mobility, best agers set the tone.
in africa, in the arab area and in latin america “active non-retirement” of best agers is still weak.
in east asia, central europe and russia, “active non-retirement” of best agers leads to a shift in values.
the effects of demographic change on young people have so far hardly been researched.
there is uncertainty as to whether best agers will adapt sustainable lifestyles or tend towards catching up on luxury consumption with problematic environmental consequences.
young and old exchange ideas even more closely: germany's ability to innovate will be maintained when all generations are successfully integrated into the labor market.
the exchange of knowledge and experience in the workplace is most successful in a cross-age dialogue.
the future development of the system of vocational training represents a requirement for research and innovation.
the demands of the newly emerging senior citizen milieus on the education and occupational system will change significantly - for example, as a result of workforces with a high average age.
employees actively participate in working life much longer than ever before, highly qualified retirees continue to work as senior experts.
the knowledge society is shaped by the growing demand and necessity for lifelong learning.
the stagnating and declining population figures in numerous european countries are intensified in rural areas by the loss of importance of agriculture and forestry and migration to urban areas.
the existence of numerous german villages is threatened, and many are gradually disappearing from the map.
rural areas in eastern germany suffer most from the decline of villages.
the depopulation in rural areas leads to falling revenues for the municipalities and, at the same time, increases the per capita costs for public tasks.
by providing benefits such as clean water and good health conditions, villages are pilot cases for shaping the post-growth society.
the main driver for the threat of the existence of german villages is the declining economic importance of agriculture and forestry in connection with demographic factors.
the migration to the cities reached a peak, they are regarded as more attractive because of education, labor market and lifestyle.
the survival of individual villages is mainly determined by factors such as geographical and scenic location and the accessibility of infrastructures within a short driving time.

these factors determine if someone wants to live in a village: sufficiently younger residents, visibility of vacancies, initiative of the citizens and local politics, real estate ownership and previous investment decisions in infrastructures.
smaller villages are overall more at risk to disappear than larger ones, but the connection to a high-performance it infrastructure and the energy transition offer prospects for village.
efficient it connections create new opportunities for education, work and more modern lifestyles and thus increase the attractiveness of the village compared to the city.
the energy transition with the promotion of biomass utilization, wind power and photovoltaics is mainly being implemented in the countryside.
new acquisition opportunities, including installation, servicing and maintenance of systems, develop villages 3.0.
villages and the urban vs. rural structure have so far only rarely been seen in research and innovation.

under the restrictions of a declining population and the difficult financing of public expenditure, conditions are found in the villages that are also of crucial importance for the post-growth society.

villages are pilot locations for inexpensive, decentralized sewage systems, small schools with new forms of learning, a mixture of mobile and central health services and care with the support of civil society.
the relationship between humans and the cultural landscape and nature is deeply affected by the decline of villages, knowledge about everyday life in rural areas disappeared.
villages as pilot locations for the post-growth society require dialogues with citizens about new forms of community.
enduring friendships - be they real or virtual - are increasingly important for both individuals and society.
anyone who maintains and lives long-term friendships not only feels subjectively more satisfied, but also more resilient and anchored in social life.
it is scientifically proven that those who find support in friendships live longer and healthier, are more stress-resistant, self-confident and trustworthy.

people are more likely to resort to advice from friends and no longer see it as a counterpart social contacts are subordinate to partners or relatives. friendships are increasingly becomming the center of everyday life.
in our individualized society, friendships are replacing positions that were previously filled by the family, by organically grown life contexts and biological relationships.
since partners and employers change frequently, having one's own family is no longer a matter of course, friendships become one of the “central relay stations of social cohesion.
there is evidence of the close connection between good friendships, health, life expectancy and demographic development.
the state of health of people with close social ties is far better than that of people without social support.
in the netherlands, friendship programs are designed to protect older women and men from being alone.
web 3.0 and new media, which are used for visual and virtual communication act as drivers for friendship programs.
increasing mobility and the constant availability of virtual social networks led to friendships that are mainly lived in virtual space.
the trend towards artificially and naturally enhancing friendships affects numerous fields of research and innovation.
the health sciences, biomedicine and brain research, are dealing with the positive psychosomatic effects of friendship.
innovations in the field of architecture and living, which try to respond to the growing importance of friendships, help to maintain friendships.
the developments in the field of ict (information and communications technology) and new media emphasizes the importance of virtual friendships.
a comparison between oecd countries showed that in the usa, where people are in particularly close contact with their friends, have a more positive basic mood.
in countries like hungary or japan, where people spend less time with their friends, show signs to have improvable mental health.
germany is in the middlefield in maintaining friendships, while strengthening them can have a positive effect on the perceived quality of life and the feeling of security of the people.
the relationship between humans and animals changed: in many cultures animals are no longer perceived and understood as things, but increasingly as closely related to humans.
animals are understood as intelligent and capable of suffering, and overall as fellow beings, further questions about how humans deal with animals led to further equality between both of them.
research from biology, cognitive and brain research show that animals have numerous cognitive and social skills that are available to them to an extent that had not been previously attributed.
keeping pets is a center of life in various social milieus around the world, accompanied by a strong humanization of animals.
animal rights and welfare rank high in values, with climate policy as well as environmental and agricultural research putting argumentative pressure on animal breeding and meat production.
agricultural experts doubt that the meat industry in its current state is sustainable enough in view of ecological and demographic challenges.
vegetarian, vegan and animal welfare movements are more professional and found wide resonance in cultural and ethical discourses and in the media.
leading philosophers deal with the social construction of the human-animal relationship.
the topic of human-animal conviviality is a transdisciplinary research field that is suitable for a social dialogue process in which research has to play an essential role as a balancing body.
alternative solutions for animal use in agriculture and nutrition, such as in-vitro meat or the cultivation of microorganisms in closed reactors as animal feed or food supplements are a standard.
new discourse alliances are redirecting bioeconomy and agricultural research for more stringent control of animal experiments in medicine and behavioral research.
animal needs, welfare, health and relations are developing into new demand factors for technological innovations and service innovations.
large parts of the german population feels annoyed not only by road and air traffic noise, but also by industrial and neighborhood noise.
citizens' initiatives against noise are gaining in popularity, and there are increasing media-effective lawsuits against private individuals or municipalities and companies.
mounting evidence from the scientific community show the harmful effects of noise on health.
the public's call for political measures to reduce noise pollution is becoming increasingly audible.
politicians are devoting themselves to the environmental problem of noise, not least in response to increasing expectations from the population.

it is undisputed that noise causes considerable damage to health and increases the risk of numerous diseases, including cardiovascular diseases, tinnitus, cognitive developmental disorders in children and depression.
according to the who, western europe alone has lost more than a million healthy years of life due to health impairments caused by noise.
there is evidence of harmful effects of industrial noise on wildlife and indications of indirect negative effects of noise on plants.
more and more citizens' initiatives are being founded to protest against noise, and the topic of aircraft noise in particular is attracting a great deal of media attention.
general complaints against noise from municipal facilities or events such as sports or folk festivals are increasing.
the drivers of the globally increasing noise pollution are widely known: growing urbanization as well as road, air and rail traffic are causing increasing civilization noise.

exposure to noise has another subjective component: whether a noise is perceived as noise depends on personal and economic interests as well as on the individual attitude towards the source of the noise.
the question of personal contribution to reducing noise pollution in everyday life, for example by taking possible noise pollution into account when purchasing a product, has not yet been answered.
there are gaps in research on dose-effect relationships of noise in diseases such as tinnitus that are becoming more and more common.
when it comes to noise reduction, relevant research and innovation areas are engineering to reduce industrial and traffic noise.
noise exposure negatively affect human cognitive abilities: recent studies show a connection between noise exposure and learning and memory disorders in children.

technical innovations led to an increase in energy and resource consumption instead of savings, due to the rebound effect: a phenomenon that measures to improve energy and resource efficiency have the unintended effect of increased use.
sustainability efforts could be undermined by the effect of using more technical measures that make energy consumption more ethical, but are therefore used more widely.

the increase in energy consumption is an indirect result of the technical measures meant to increase efficiency: the demand for products and services increased because they are now more cost-effective.
improvements in efficiency led to an increase in aggregate demand.
between 30 percent and over 100 percent of the expected savings through increased efficiency cannot be achieved due to the overall higher use of the technologies.
the overall higher use of the technologies, even if efficient, has largely not been taken into account in research and energy politics.

the drivers of rebound effects are researched in more detail: in addition to the factor of increased demand due to falling costs, there are indications of sociological and psychological influencing factors.
the overall higher use of the technologies, even if efficient, is the most complex phenomena that can counteract the intentions of innovations in the field of sustainability.
the interactions between resource consumption and efficiency as well as the rebound effects of new technologies and applications are examined.
innovative approaches to decoupling growth from energy and resource consumption are of great interest.
the change in consumption patterns is decisive for future disposal and possible environmental problems due to the material flows linked to it.
consumer goods such as clothing, automobiles and insulation materials for residential properties are characterized by an ever-increasing variety of materials and complex material composites.
disposal systems are still geared towards less complex materials, making them unable to recycle the variety of today's materials.
as a result of corrosion and wear, built-in materials like in buildings, systems, transformers, pipes and cables, set free harmful substances into the environment.
the location, distribution, nature and dynamics of negative environmental effects are still only known sporadically.
consumption patterns only change through a complex interplay, especially between market participants, technological change and governance.
consumption patterns reflect the preferences of their time, such as mobile communication or reducing the energy consumption of residential buildings.
infrastructures, products and materials have a lifespan of hundreds of years (e.g. bridges) to two decades (e.g. automobiles) up to a few days (e.g. food packaging).
consumption patterns, such as the changing material composition of goods, and anticipated future environmental problems and raw material requirements created a wideranging sustainable solutionism.
cars that need to be disposed are mainly made of plastic fences, light metals and electronics that cannot be recovered satisfactorily with conventional shredder technology.
the effects of past, present and future consumption patterns on disposal of substances into the environment are known entirely.
material dynamics and their future consequences for disposal and the environment are still not sufficiently received by the research and innovation system.
there is an increasing need to “defuse” so-called “time bombs” of consumption, such as plastics.
knowledge of material issues in connection with consumption, their temporal dynamics and environmental relevance is likely to gain importance in densely populated areas.
the resource-poor country germany is committed to sustainable development and re-creates 100% from waste.
the increasing average body weight in western countries has prompted the world health organization (who) to declare a global obesity epidemic.
global obesity has led to diverse efforts at various levels of control, all aim to encourage citizens to adopt a weight-reducing lifestyle.
people are addressing a discourse that divides them into risk groups and encourages them to actively take sides in the conflict over obesity.
widespread fears are expressed about the health consequences of obesity and its long-term economic costs.
equating weight loss with a health benefit is scientifically controversial: this assumption leads to numerous campaigns and media reports to encourage citizens to lose weight.

driven by medicine, nutritional science, health policy, mass media as well as the fitness and beauty industry, cultural norms about non-fat bodies as healthy on the one hand and about fat, disease-prone bodies as deviating on the other hand.
obese bodies are often wrongly interpreted as unaesthetic and an expression of a person's failure to discipline themselves.
health campaigns center the body as an object of consumption and a symbol of performance.
stigmatization and discrimination against fat people intensified, which also plays a role in a growing number of psychological problems with regard to eating, exercise and sport.
the social controversy over the "obesity epidemic" provokes active political support.
research is looking for medical, surgical and pharmacological solutions to the obesity problem, but also for nutrition and exercise.
mixed-reality video games offer playful opportunities for intervention and light sports.
technical and media options for self-monitoring, self-measurement and self-discipline for public health-enhancement are part of the portfolio of activities in research and innovation.
exercise concepts bring together urban planning, mobility and traffic engineering in order to challenge physical movement.
the overall pressure on research and innovation increases mainly in terms of health applications.
the increase of personal nutrition and exercise skills support the tasks of health education.
psychology, therapy and media educational formats are increasingly providing differentiated offers to increase public health.
beauty and youthfulness are increasingly becoming a duty to all people.
physical and mental performance, an attractive appearance and a winning demeanor are becoming more relevant for social recognition and professional success.
attractive people receive higher salaries than less attractive people.
more people feel under pressure to meet social expectations and begin to shape themselves externally and internally.
resilience, flexibility, willingness to perform, creativity and a confident demeanor are just some of the requirements that are explicitly required in today's job advertisements.
not everyone can withstand the beauty standards and expectations and the actual demands of professional reality.

latest findings in medical research, advances in neuroscience and in the field of information and communication technologies are increasingly expanding the spectrum of possible measures to improve physical and mental health.
doctors from various disciplines offer services that go beyond curative medicine and aim to increase the overall beauty and youthfullness of their patients.
doctors from various disciplines are aiming less at health than at increasing performance and attractiveness.
cosmetic surgery continues to be a booming market.
the tendency of getting wrinkle treatments with injections is increasing, especially in men.
improving mental performance through substitutes is increasingly relevant.
the consumption of brain food, freely available stimulants, and prescription psychotropic drugs, are the range of options to temporarily increase the cognitive performance.
the knowledge and education about long-term psychological and physical side effects of brain stimulants – prescriptive or freely available – is still insufficiently widespread.
new trends in psychological self-conditioning are emerging, ranging from techniques to self-optimize to the use of technical applications.
scientific knowledge increasingly tries to use classic methods such as meditation, to self-optimize.
various self-monitoring technologies are used, such as medical health applications.
collected health data is publicly accessible via social networks.
optimizing mental performance leads to better professional results on the one hand, but can also lead to health problems such as burnout on the other hand.
questions of preventive occupational health and safety have a high priority in the context of optimizing mental performance.
the knowledge society places very high demands on its members, requiring the optimization of mental performance.
people see themselves forced to increase their mental capacity with artificial measures in order to be able to keep up with the competition of the knowledge society.
dealing with dying and death is ambivalent: dying and death are either being pushed out of public life, altough every second person in germany has already thought about their own death.
the majority of people wish for a sudden, unexpected and pain-free death in a familiar environment and with close friends and relatives.
most people today still die in institutions such as nursing homes or hospitals, altough they wish to to be in a familiar environment.
developing a dignified culture of death is a social challenge that not only nursing homes or hospitals have to face, but also the society as a whole.
dying is still determined by cultural, religious and social conditions, more than personal wishes.
demographic change, the longevity of society, but also developments in intensive care medicine influence death.
the goal of modern medicine - to prevent dying and to prolonging life - appears to be in contradiction to pain-relieving, "more acceptable" palliative treatment.
most citizens in germany have drawn up an advance directive, mainly because of fear of medical oversupply.
the number of people planning such an advance directive is increasing steadily.
the discussions about active and passive euthanasia are the urgent questions of modern medicine and ethics.
passive euthanasia raises besides ethical, also social design questions: how can the danger of medical over- or undersupply at the end of life be countered?
pressure on thoughts about 'renouncing life' for economic reasons continue to grow.
alternative concepts for the dying process, such as palliative medicine or active and passive euthanasia are implemented in the medical law.
health and care structures are adapted to meet people's frequent requests for a humane death within their own four walls.
new processes about how to handle a person's digital data, crypto, health data and more after their death are implemented.
the basic right to informational self-determination and the general right of personality form the basis for the regulation of digital property after the death of a person.
legal conflicts between heirs and providers of internet platforms have arisen.
relatives can receive access to the digital goods of the deceased, but this can be denied if they do not have digital access keys.
the concept of property in a digitized society focuses on virtual goods and thus, must be declared.
to regulate digital estate, a distinction must be made between private property and business property.
private digital estate includes photos, e-mails, video and audio data and online profiles as well as crypto currencies and personal cloud infrastructures.
business digital estate is customer data that has been owned by the person who passed away. the data stocks are increasingly of ideal and material value even after death.
access to digital electronic accounts and insurances for relatives can be existential, therefore, a digital access key needs to be passed on.
there are hardly any binding rules on how to deal with a person's digital estate after their death.
the right to close a digital account after the death of a person is handled by the providers of the digital infrastructure.
the contracts with digital service providers automatically expire with the death of the contractor.
a comprehensive range of digital services for managing the digital estate of death contractors is being developed as a business model and legally checked.
digital property and inheritance still lacks regulations.
the death of a data owner can be a barrier to innovation if a person death means the operator's denial of access.
the death of a data owner can be a barrier to innovation if the information available can no longer be used by the heirs, thus restricting the transfer of knowledge.
services for the management of digital assets of deceased people are gaining importance.
due to the increasing use of digital identities, conflicts in dealing with data and traces of deceased people on the internet are to be expected.
questions of long-term storage and access to data also arise for databases of private individuals.
the industry association bitkom advises relatives to observe the digital legacy just as carefully as paper documents, as important information for surviving dependents can be found there.
a new culture of preservation of knowledge is developing. it now includes new forms of commemoration and mourning - such as a digital mourning culture.
privacy and data protection are guaranteed in virtual space.
digital society is aware of the topic of personal digital inheritance in the long term.
social design tasks include the preparation of committees for the new challenge of personal digital inheritance.
trust is the most important prerequisite for the functioning of social system.
a decisive change in the culture of trust can be observed on the internet.
variable user identities cause a loss of trust and reputation of people, products and services online.
it will be more difficult to refute the suspicion that your own recommendations have been paid for.
not only digital products and services, but also opinions are increasingly under the general suspicion of profit-generating marketing.
the internet merely offers the technical framework for an increasing social need for detailed information on products and people.
new types of internet services, such as „klout“, create personal online record reputation, containing comments, prefferences, networks and more and aim to create a digital twin of the user itself.
nine billion people worldwide use the social network meta to present themselves and their activities online.
the disclosure of personal interests and wishes leads to people being researched online in order to get an initial assessment of them.
ubiquitous transparency allows very personal details about a person to come to light to create trust.
the usage of the web 3.0 enables everyone to receive information on other people instantly and thus creates trust.
digital services such as peerindex derive their influence from the web activities of an internet user and place his online behaviour on a defined scale.
a specific index can be used as a universal indicator for a persons 'or companies' reputation, products or services in the real world.
parameters of the trust index are used to determine the digital reputation, but are still highly controversial, as they are already being used for both private and professional decisions.
wired magazine reports on cases in which applications for advertised positions have been rejected due to a digital trust index score that is too low.
there have been important research activities on digital trust reputation in germany, conducted by hiig and weizenbaum institute.
it is necessary to pursue the question of the extent to which a “virtual reputation” can be applied to everyday life outside the internet and what consequences occur from that.
the rights holders still try to protect their digital content in the traditional way, e.g. by using copy protection techniques to prevent improper distribution.
initiatives are publicly calling for a new digital copyright law, as the traditional way of using copy protection techniques does not offer proper protection.
a legal clarification of digital property has taken place, the general understanding of the original and the copy changed significantly overall thanks to blockchain technologies.
internet users deal creatively with the diversity of digital cultural assets and create nft's.
there is an increasing awareness of the innovation potential through open data.
the digitization and distribution of copyrighted materials over the internet makes it easier to save, copy, modify and redistribute content.
there are user and owner licenses, derived from nfts, but none of the approaches currently has the potential for a widely accepted solution.
too little knowledge of such digital owner licences exists in large parts of the population.
the intensive use of digital technologies in the population increased the demand for handling digital content of all kinds individually - be it scientific texts, images, music or film material.
the majority of intellectual property that is protected by copyright is being infringed online, for example when parts of a piece of music are used in the production of a film.
since the use of digital media has to be seen in a global context, adapting national copyright law is only one component.
the creative combination of existing content to create something new is seen as potentially innovative, rigid copyright regulations can prove to be barriers to innovation.
the relationship between copy and original is redefined, the copy is no longer worse than the original.
science and research are directly affected by the reuse of research results, the open access and open data movement caused a shift in ownership.
the critical view of the digitization of popular cultural assets inhibits the innovation-inhibiting effect of a standstill in artistic originality.
in a world characterized by information and knowledge as a resource, people increasingly dependent on the accessibility and usability of digital content.

the simple integration and utilization of digital content for one's own work is essential to be able to use existing knowledge in the best possible way, to further develop it and to be able to pass it on.
digitization and networking characterize our society and internet users accept far-reaching encroachments on their privacy.
in order to be able to use new technologies and possibilities, internet users accept far-reaching encroachments on their privacy.
our society faces a state in which there is no longer any privacy or data protection.
internet users increasingly reject new technologies and withdraw from the internet.
95 percent of all internet users in germany are registered in at least one social network.
60 million germans voluntarily reveal their personal data and profiles on meta, where data protection scandals occur almost every day.
although more and more personal information is being hacked or stolen, the outrage of internet users is limited, a change in usage behavior cannot be identified.
the majority of society wants to take advantage of the many opportunities online and knowingly or unknowingly accepts a partial loss of control over private data.
new services and technical possibilities are gratefully accepted and used without hesitation or privacy concerns.
despite the dangers to data protection and privacy, cloud computing, social commerce and online banking are part of everyday life in our society.
a trend is emerging under the catchphrase post-privacy that regards data protection and privacy as a relic from the pre-digital era.
post-privacy supporters attach too little importance to the decision-making power of the internet user and explain that the new technical developments are inevitable and unchangeable.

privacy and data protection is out of sight of the providers: users of social networks have dealt with the technical privacy settings of the respective network and have adapted or changed them as far as possible.
further data protection scandals led to an increased withdrawal of users from commercial offers and to the rejection of new technologies and developments.
the economic consequences of the mass withdrawal of internet users are the loss of financial worth of data.
digital networking, exchange and discussion are the most important drivers for research and innovation.
changes in the behavior of internet users have far-reaching consequences for innovation and research.
continuous efforts and innovations in the field of it security to protect privacy are necessary.
new technologies and networking are the basis of the knowledge society and essential for its functioning.
in most areas and aspects of our everyday activities, people interact with increasingly complex and non-transparent software-intensive system networks.
the increasing autonomy of machine systems is the result of a delegation of decision-making powers to machines.
the adaptivity of machine systems is increased to an extent that allows flexible action by the user, machines are optimally adapted to the needs of the user.
the social challenge is to grant people the freedom to make decisions about what level of technology and delegation they choose.
autonomous, open, socio-technical system networks, the so-called cyber-physical systems (cps), create optimally adapted machines that anticipate the needs of the users.
cyber-physical systems (cps) are used in all areas of life, for example in industrial production, in health care, in energy supply or in road traffic.
business criteria, such as production capacity utilization, increased efficiency and reduced personnel costs, are the drivers of the implementation of cyber-physical systems (cps) everywhere.
cyber-physical systems originally developed for industrial production are used in private households.
the spread of system networks in private households necessitates innovations in software and hardware engineering.
individual and social need structures between autonomy and control deal with the future of human-machine teams.
new forms of stereotypical user models represent a barrier to innovation and oppose the trend towards increasing personalization of products and services.

the availability, selection and dissemination of data, information and knowledge is influenced by cyber-physical systems - be it via "intelligent", semantic, ubiquitous systems, medical monitoring and emergency services (aal) or new forms of participation in educational offers (e.g. virtual universities).
uavs (unmanned, uninhabited or unpiloted aerial vehicle) ar equipped with various devices, such as film and photo cameras, infrared sensors, measuring devices and radar technology.
uavs (unmanned, uninhabited or unpiloted aerial vehicle) are controlled remotely via various control devices or via preprogrammed algorithms.
uavs (unmanned, uninhabited or unpiloted aerial vehicle) are not only used for military purposes, but also for civilian applications, for example in disaster control or in plant inspection.
drones are cheap and easy to build and use, they are now mostly used by amateurs in the private sector.
miniaturization, falling prices and a large, creative hobbyist scene are the driving foces behind the popularization of drones for the private use.
“amateur drones” are controlled by computers, radios and cell phones and form the foundation of a new amateur movement.
amateur drone communities are formed in which instructions for self-construction are exchanged, but limits come from flight regulations and battery life.
business models for drone-based services, such as delivery services, are popular.

any unmanned flying objects in germany that weights less than five kilograms is granted a temporary permit for operation up to 100 meters above ground, but they are not allowed to fly over crowds or locations of police and security authorities.
drones take on functions in social relationships, they will - like the pc - represent a platform for innovations of the future.
questions arise about control and privacy protection when it comes to technical innovations.
the federal ministry of the interior demands that access to drone technology should be designed in such a way that abuse, for example attacks, spying on privacy, is pre-built.
the massive use of private drones pose negative effects on trust and discretion with regard to privacy, causing changes in narrative structures and forms in public communication.
media and journalism are increasingly influenced by the use of drones.
drones in journalism and in private photography are an important visual language, shaped by the "view from above“.
intensive computer and video games are increasingly having an impact on social behavior in society.
intensive computer and video games led to experimentation with new ideas and developed into social innovations.
persuasive games are developed and used with the aim of practicing positive behavior and shaping values.
the human instinct to play video games is used to increase intrinsic motivation.
gamification is being used in commercial communication as well as other areas of life in order to attract a high level of attention and participation.
the application potential of gamification lies particularly in education and health education, but also in employee motivation, customer loyalty and in innovation processes.
examples of gamification are the chromaroma game run by the london public transport company that increase motivation in employees.
the rise of gamification reflects the rapidly increasing number of users for computer and online games in all age groups.
findings from cognitive research are increasingly being integrated into educational concepts that demonstrate the positive effects of gamification in promoting behavior and motivation.
the international market for computer and online games is the fastest growing area in the software sector.
computer games are complex since virtual game worlds are converge with the real environment, for example in connection with the player's location-based data.
elements of typical online games are tested and used in the work environment to increase motivation or to induce behavioral training.
gamification permeates more and more social sub-areas and thus gains importance in all fields of innovation.

online games have effects on the decision-making behavior of an entire generation in terms of solution orientation, intuitive action, collaboration, experimentation and willingness to take risks and thus strengthen the willingness to innovate and the associated skills.

new approaches to creative learning methods or “serious games” through gamification offer the opportunity to create flexible instruments that enable lifelong learning in the rapidly changing world of work.
science benefits from the creative contributions of large numbers of online-game players and their intrinsic motivation, reinforcing the trend of citizen research.
the utilization of game mechanisms to increase motivation and behavioral conditioning raises ethical questions.
society has been shaped widely by global and cooperative strategy, simulation and problem-solving games from the children's room into professional life.
the occupational fields medicine and law include many routine tasks that are taken over by information technology.
numerous jobs are lost or significantly changed through automation technologies.
the loss in jobs due to automation causes far-reaching challenges for the middle class.
adequate preparation for the change in professional requirements in the digitized knowledge society is required.
industrialization shows how new technologies trigger social and economic upheavals and how traditional jobs have been replaced by the use of machines.
in the double-digit growing market for industrial robots, germany holds a leading position worldwide in terms of robot density in manufacturing.

the market in robotics is continuing to grow for highly qualified professions: electronic medical expert systems are already compiling diagnoses in hospitals, and autonomous computer algorithms are trading every millisecond on the world's high-frequency exchanges.
modern text synthesis algorithms constantly write news about events and combine stock market news into reports that can hardly be distinguished from texts by human authors.
modern text synthesis algorithms hold immense potential for innovation to save costs and increase efficiency in tarious professional fields and also in research and development.
in order to compensate for possible negative effects caused by the elimination of well-paid jobs, new needs and potentials that arise as a result of the changes are identified by policy makers.
the jobloss of low-skilled assembly line worker through rationalization is followed by the loss of the supposedly qualified knowledge worker.

the jobloss of low-skilled assembly line workers is offset by a critical discourse on the extent to which the pursuit of (profit) optimization when using automation to increase productivity is ethically justifiable.
germany positions itself within the international field of “algorithm workers”, despite mass jobloss due to this automation.
the economic and financial crisis has led to a reorientation of economic policy in the industrialized countries, causing a full resettlement of local industry to non-industrialized countries.
a full resettlement of industry in the usa and great britain to non-industrialized countries is finished.
the industrial share of the european economic output has increased from 16% to 20%.
established industrialized countries have developed into service societies, instead of production societies.
due to the industrial relocation from industrialized countries to non-industrialized countries, the share of the service sector has increased.
the technology-driven industrial sector has steadily declined in industrialized countries.
the industrial share of the us and uk decreased to 16%.
due to an industrial share decrease, job losses can only partly be absorbed by the service sector.
few job fields migrate from the industrial to the service sector, such as the finance, insurance and corporate, which achieve productivity values ​​similar to those of the manufacturing sector.
most employees work in the area of ​​“personnel and social services”, whose productivity is the lowest in the economy as a whole.
the economic development is increasingly dependent on the service sector of ​​“personnel and social services”.
the productivity of the usa and the uk decreases between 0.3 and 0.5 percentage points each year.
the usa and uk are increasingly turning to an active industrial policy in favor of knowledge and technology-intensive industrial sectors.
germany has placed a focus on industry, in particular on the high-tech sector, showing a trend towards reindustrialization.
the industrial share of gross value added 23% in germany, which is significantly higher than in the usa or uk.
new technological developments in industrial production support reindustrialization, as countries find new industrial access through their technological competence.
the advancing digitization and intelligent linking of systems, such as iot, are leading to the fourth industrial revolution.
the focus on cyber-physical production systems (cps) enable the production of individualized products (mass customization) instead of mass production.
a driver in industrial development is the stronger convergence of production and services, the so-called hybrid value creation.
germany has a good position in the areas of technological developments and hybrid value creation: the convergence of production and services.
the reindustrialization of industrial nations leads to enormous opportunities, especially in mechanical engineering and plant engineering.
in the course of reindustrialization, international research and innovation efforts intensify globally.
more and more people are starting to manufacture products and services in private or in groups instead of buying them.
the mass movement of private manufacturing and diy enthusiasts extends to a wide variety of goods - from clothing and bicycles to software and electronic control units to energy.
value creation has significantly changed through the interaction of social developments with new technical possibilities.
the interaction of social developments with new technical possibilities mutually reinforce each other.
the link between individual creativity for identity formation and value creation in the knowledge society has led to an ever greater personalization of products.
a movement towards non-commercial, communal forms of need satisfaction, such as peer production, poses an alternative to a consumer society that is perceived as unsustainable.
the open design movement was founded through the scene of electronics hardware amateur hobbyists, the maker movement and the open source movement.
a revival of local craft traditions as a complementary movement to globalization takes place.
the revival of local craft traditions forms a mass phenomena of self-help in financial crisis situations.

the do-it-yourself movement gets support through technical enablers such as open electronic components, open source software, open design concepts, mobile workshops (“fablabs”), generative production processes (3d printing) and internet platforms to exchange concepts and sell products.
value creation patterns witin the “do it yourself movement” form innovation models and roles for all actors in the innovation system.
the conditions for addressing societal challenges change as decentralized productional structures enable new forms of governance.
do-it-yourself actors urge the teaching of creative and manual skills in kindergartens and schools.
projects such as fabrication laboratory workshops (fablabs), makes technology tangible for children and promotes access to mint subjects.
the boundaries between knowledge work, creative work and craftsmanship are looser and create new forms of education.
the swapping of clothes, shoes, furniture and other consumer goods as well as the establishment of social department stores gain importance.
more and more people who are not in need financially use professionally organized swap exchanges, private swap parties and online swap events.
exchange boxes and bookcases are publicly installed in all cities.
private initiatives mix free exchanges of private items with the commercial trade of used items.
the trend towards swapping is driven by the falling standard of living, for example in regions with an economic crisis, where people in need exchange clothes and everyday objects.
swapping is the most popular strategy for responsible and sustainable consumption.
the formation of neighborhood structures is in close connection with exchange projects.
alternative digital currencies, such as crypto currencies and reputation mechanisms make it possible to organize exchange activities beyond the immediate vicinity.
the principle of swapping is expanding to most areas.
swapping creates new requirements for products and services, for example the mobile usability by different users over a lifespan of products.
a culture of exchange produced new sustainable business models in the sense of the green economy.
in the course of the digitization and the increasing use of social media, the infrastructures are being created for the development of new markets based on exchange principles.
information processes take place virtually and the implementation takes place jointly and locally in the immediate user environment.

in a society with increased migration and a high level of cultural diversity, the need for alternatives to existing market forms that integrate different cultural requirements in terms of ownership, acquisition or use, increases.

with the problematization of the consequences of mass consumption in western industrialized countries, thought leaders question whether sustainable consumption exists at all, since the ecological and social “footprint” of every activity weights heavy.
the effects of the co2 emissions and water consumption of clothing production is constantly re-calculated and distributed towards everyones environmental footprint.

the social footprint of clothing production is taken into account more than ever: the working time per item of clothing and working conditions that violate human rights play a big role in the consumtion.
the social footprint of clothing is calculated on the basis of process chain analyzes over the product life cycle.
the environmental and social footprint can be calculated with free public tools on the internet, based on the information provided by the user.
conscious consumption through the measurement of the "personal footprint" addresses needs such as a clean environments, meaningfulness, social commitment and health.
the drivers for the spread or general establishment of the personal footprint indicator for sustainable consumption are the consequences of global warming.
the majority the of german population would like to make a significant contribution to climate protection through environmentally conscious everyday behavior.

the increasing awareness of the global ecological and social consequences of individual consumption has increased media communication, global relationships and improved the underlying scientific factual basis.
the measurement and collection of individually caused ecological and social damages (the "personal footprints”) caused changes in consumer behavior.
the pressure on citizens to measure, record and even publish their individual ecological and social footprint increased.
there is social pressure to minimize the ecological and social footprint of each individual, to reduce the personal contribution to climate change.
a driver of the growing awareness on the personal contribution to climate change are the global ecological and social consequences of individual consumption.

the social extent of the behavioural changes in individual consumption through measurement and collection of the “personal footprint” as well as their possible ecological and social consequences are still unknown.
the indirect effects of changed consumption patterns towards more sustainability have disruptive potential on innovation.
key innovations in consumption patterns are the interaction of customers with shopping assistance systems.
key innovation drivers in consumtion patterns are the databases required for measuring the ecological and social footprint of each individual.
the measurement of each individuals' social and ecological footprint raises awareness and increases the pressure on sustainable production and consumption.
the fast-fashion is still consumed more intensily than high street fashion.

the global success of fast-fashion is based in particular on the fact that these companies manage to produce clothes in the shortest possible time that are trendy for a few weeks and can be sold at a low price.
many customers dispose fast fashion immediately after wearing and buy new clothes.
a significant shortening of the product lifecycle can be observed with products beyond fast-fashion.
there is a trend that propagates the purchase of high-quality, durable goods as sustainable consumption.
cheap fast-fashion has shaped the shopping behavior of an entire generation with their concept: products with a short lifespan that are so cheap, that everyone can afford them.
in the usa, a person buys an average of 64 items of clothing per year, many of which are already wandering around after a few weeks in the trash.
the over consumtion of fast-fashion is not a form of extreme shopping, but a widespread consumer behavior.
