over consumption (of fast-fashion and other products with a short lifespan) is countered by the trend that more and more people are demanding services and products with longer manufacturing and usage times.
sustainability-oriented providers of regional products as well as traditional manufacturers of high-quality products such as clothing or luxury items meet the needs of more and more people.
designer goods manufacturerers offer customers the repair of old or damaged bags of any brand as a service.
automobile manufacturers such as volvo decided to only upgrade their models, instead of producing new ones, so that the lifecycle can be extended while using technical innovations.
the demand to decouple economic growth from garbage, instead of living in a throwaway society, has particular relevance for the future demand for consumer goods such as clothing.
in addition to rethinking development, production and sales of consumer goods, there are also innovations for the entire infrastructure, including for retrofitting.
while in some areas of technology, for example software, upgrades is already widely used, the question of transferability remains for consumer goods.
the focus on longevity in consumer behavior carried over to other areas, such as science and research, where the term “slow science” describes longer working cycles.
crowdsourcing, work and creative processes are outsourced to a large number of individuals by breaking down complex tasks into smaller tasks, processed by different people to make them manageable.
crowdfunding is used to collect money for a project or company with the help of many smaller investments by a large number of financiers via special crowdfunding platforms.
pre-selected start-ups are presented to a crowd of potential micro-investors, each of whom can easily invest in the company with a sum of at least 250 euros.
investors can benefit from the company's growth by paying out the increase in value proportionally and in addition to the participation as a profit after a minimum investment period.

crowdfunding as a financing model for start-ups and social innovations is only just beginning to develop, but the need on the part of founders and activists is just as great as the willingness of people to invest privately in crowdfunding projects.

two factors are essential drivers for the increasing spread of crowdfunding: web 3.0 as the technical basis, as it enables participatory processes worldwide, and the further development of online and micropayment models.
crowdfunding has positive effects for social innovations and new services, which are seen as drivers for innovations in other industries.

crowdfunding of innovative small businesses supports innovations directly and indirectly, since the success or failure of crowdfunding projects provide important information about the market for investors and vc donors (proof of concept).
crowdfunding often bypasses banks and retailers by creating a connection between customer and manufacturer: a sign of a new industrial regime.
the first crowdfunding services by professional financial sectors are emerging.
crowdfunding is a challenge for the conventional financial system, whose players fear competition from the it world.
crowdfunding has transferred to science.
concepts like the open science model opens the scientific process for those involved outside of professional science.
networking through internet-based technologies successfully solve scientific questions and problems by utilizing crowdsourcing.
trends and forms of financing from the financial sector show expansion and supplementation by non-financial premises.
traditional return-driven investment criteria are weakened.
banks often only play a peripheral role in the financing of business models.

microfinances and microinsurances are lending small sums or policies to poor and rural small business owners, who would otherwise not receive any capital due to a lack of infrastructure or creditworthiness.

concepts for the financial inclusion of people with lower income (banking the unbanked) apply worldwide, as a growing number of private debtors without checking accounts or credit cards are falling out of the formal financial system.
mobile banking operated by network operators and telecommunications companies, are creating a high impact in developing countries.
with the unconventional use of simple it such as sms, low-income consumers, but also small traders are enabled to do financial transactions over the phone.
mission or impact investing are generic terms for investments that assess not only returns but also ethical, religious, social and ecological dimensions.

value-based financial services drives the recognition that a lack of access to capital and a rigid understanding of creditworthiness based on western standards are major obstacles to further economic development.
communication technologies allow new customer groups and service providers access to the financial market and enable the coupling of previously separated financial value-added segments.
the increased self-confidence of religious groups leads to the search for investment opportunities related to their religion.
consumers and companies lost confidence in banks due to the financial crisis, which spurred the search for new forms of financing.
an attempt is made to bring economic, value-based and cultural criteria for investing into a new “justification order”.

the importance of the banks decreased, while money decisions for citizens become more detailed, faster, more momentous, but also more comprehensible, for example when a smallholder is given a microcredit.
teaching citizens and groups, such as school students about finance, created financial literacy is an important guideline for the knowledge society.
a social provision for the future is increasingly dependent on the availability of long-term capital.

strategic investments, for example in the construction of infrastructures such as roads and public transport, innovation financing, climate protection or the restructuring of energy and agricultural systems around the world require a lot of patience and cannot be shouldered by the state alone.
the global investment requirement for infrastructure updates alone is estimated at three trillion us dollars per year and private co-investments are therefore necessary.
investments, for example in energy systems, promise steady returns, but will only materialize over longer periods of time.
in the global financial markets, owners of capital are increasingly concentrating on minimizing risks and generating short-term returns over long-term returns.
studies of globally managed assets estimate that less than a quarter of capital owners and managers worldwide are currently considering long-term investment strategies.
exorbitant amounts of capital are looking for investment opportunities globally.
key areas of services of general interest, such as infrastructure or innovation financing, suffer from a lack of capital.
there is a gap between the investment requirement and the allocation premises of the capital markets.
financial service providers have sharpened their risk management instruments due to the financial crisis.
the imponderables of long-term complex investments with all their technological, political, regulatory and systemic risks come to the fore.
the strengths of long-term investments, like long amortization periods and above-average returns opportunities, will lose weight because they are difficult to measure, evaluate and more secure.
investors prefer immediately priced, less volatile and liquid asset classes including money market and commodity transactions with the highest possible return that can be reallocated quickly.
experts speak of “unfuturization” when the investment goals can no longer be captured beyond a radius of a few years.
state regulations, like capital requirements or approval and mediation procedures, unintentionally exacerbate this risk aversion.
global politics is confronted with investment-intensive generation tasks - such as securing the food supply for more than 8.7 billion people.
institutional investors focus on the long return horizon, such as pension funds, sovereign wealth funds or foundations.
the trend of "de-fututization" is an important field for research and innovation, as there are paradigm shifts towards short-term investments due to the new challenges.
education and science are regarded as risky from an investor's point of view, due to their lengthy, open-ended processes.
private funding for educational institutions suffers due to long-term capital drying up.
the world economic forum identified chronic financial imbalances as the greatest risk factor for the world.
studies show that economists hardly know the knock-on effects during the financial crisis, since they expect “fundamental transformations” in business models and corporate culture.
forecasts are more difficult due to the fact that banks in emerging countries are rapidly gaining importance in the world economy, while barely giving out information.
a nation-state approach to financial supervision based on the regulatory agreement has led to action on macroprudential oversight of the global financial system.
in order to curb the destabilizing effect of the bond markets, debt limits for the separation of investment and commercial banks are applied globally.
the formation of regional alliances agreed on internal regulations to control the financial sector and negotiate with other regional alliances.
a "g2 global financial economy" in which the usa and china coordinate or pursue conflicting goals protect their domestic markets.

a multipolar integration and supranational regulation of the financial markets led to the establishment of a world financial authority, which includes financial supervisory authorities, central banks and representatives of the finance ministries.
far-reaching competencies damaged the reputation of the market economy and globalization, induces nation states to adopt an anti-cyclical economic policy or even protectionist intervention.
in the worst case states are being foreclosed from the global economic market.
social trends show that the global economy is in the worst-case scenario: a long phase of stagnation.
scenarios for the future of the financial system are influenced by the density and international convergence of regulatory initiatives.
leaders of the central banks shift their focus from economic growth to the relocation of capital and production of emerging economies.
the concentration of fewer actors in the banking sector take place.
the renewed strength of financial institutions take on banking-like tasks without being subject to banking supervision.
an increasing national debt crises occurs.
speculative bubbles take place in commodity markets.

improved standards for risk management, transparency and remuneration are shifted from the standardization and automation of financial market business to the development of a climate of trust in the financial system.
the financial crisis has led to highly regarded cultural studies statements and initiated an interdisciplinary discourse between economic, social and natural scientists.
the measurement and mapping of economic and social performance and ecological requirements show a paradigm shifts towards stagnation.
quality of life, growth and sustainable prosperity are globally most important to the civil society.
decoupling prosperity and environmental consumption to enable a fair distribution of prosperity nationally and globally has become the main goal.
treating not only the economy, but also the human, social, natural and health as a capital is a main value to the society.
scientific and socio-philosophical debates center around the limits of economic growth.
a high level of sensitivity for environmental and climatic issues in the population is the new normal.
work is being carried out on alternatives to gross domestic product (gdp) as an exclusive indicator of social progress.
across the world, passionate debates are being held in science, civil society, economics and ethics to an extent to which prosperity is possible without economic growth.
the uncertainty about the further development of social cohesion, national economies and public finances are just as worrying for people as the climate change and the loss of biodiversity.
as a result of the financial crisis, social movements, political institutions and business representatives are intensively involved in the debate about solutions to the climate change.
initiatives for the operationalization of quality of life and sustainability indice as governance criteria as well as systemic criticism for the renewal or normative taming of capitalism.
a constructive-critical attitude predominates civil society, which forms new ways of integration and coordination of societies.
the political discourse does not yet have any mature and democratic control options for the establishment of growth limits.
different political, economic, philosophical and civil society lines of discussion have been largely unrelated to one another.
the work of the bundestag enquete commission “growth, prosperity, quality of life" paths the way to sustainable businesses and social progress in the social market economy.
the development of knowledge- and research-based answers to the limits of growth pose an important contribution to national services.
a driver for the development of knowledge- and research-based answers to the limits of growth is the increasing complexity of technology.
problems with patent law in the field of ict is a central key technology and also indirectly raised by other technology areas.
the integrity of the patent system plays a central role in innovation in patent-intensive technologies such as ict.
debates about the usefulness of the patent system as an instrument for promoting innovations intensified.
the global financial and economic crisis hit public finances worldwide.
the national debt of the western industrial nations grew on average from 72% of the gross domestic product (gdp) in 2000 to almost 95% today.
in the uk, the us and japan, the debt ratio has increased significantly from 120% to almost 200% of gdp.
without strong fiscal policy adjustments, the national debt of industrialized countries rose from around 100% of gdp to 133%.
the national debt is at 90% of gdp and dampens economic growth.
with a debt rate of currently around 80%, germany is in the midfield of the oecd countries.
“business as usual” caused an increase to over 200% of national debt in gdp in germany.
states only have options for dealing with debt which are associated with massive risks.
the suspension of debt servicing and the negotiation of a payment waiver with creditors was successful in individual cases, but destabilized the global economy on a broad front.
an inflation policy as a coping option for dealing withglobal debt, led to a devaluation of wealth and real income.
options for dealing with debt are reducing government spending and improving the state's income situation through tax increases.
options for dealing with global debt can be measured comparatively, as they are at the center of the recommendations for budget consolidation.

possible measures to reduce government spending include reducing social benefits, savings in the public sector, structural cuts in the pension system, increased efficiency and privatization of the health system, pricing of education through tuition fees, and broadening income tax and sales tax, the reduction of subsidies and the collection of environmental taxes such as co2 taxes.
there are regulations for self-limiting politics as option for dealing with global debt, through spending caps, regulations on budget balancing, or legally binding spending cuts.
measures to deal with global debt create confidence in expectations and fiscal stability.
it is unclear whether fiscal restrictions have a consolidating or inhibiting effect on economic variables such as private investment and consumption.
an increasing share of public budgets is bound to health, care and pension expenditure.
fiscal restrictions have a significant impact on future-oriented investments such as education, research or infrastructures, which have to compete with urgent policy areas.
fiscal restrictions accelerate the shift in global r&d budgets towards emerging players.
in contrast to the club property, the common property is "rival", i. h. it is consumed with use.
a good is a common good, if the use is neither restricted nor regulated.
common goods belongs to a group of people in common, but differ from the public good by access restriction.
common goods are gaining in importance and are being discussed as a sustainable form of economy.
common goods made in self-regulated collective managements have shown that rival goods by the users, of both privatization and government, are superior.
the image of homo oeconomicus, who destroys common goods (“tragedy of the commons”), is called into question.
people act in the common interest when an appropriate framework exists.
commons in economy works through jointly developed controls and sanctions, to which the members bow out of conviction, transparency in the operating principles and conflict resolution mechanisms.
the state plays an accompanying role for common goods, for example as a trustee.
the primary driver for commons in economy are the drastic lowering of the costs of cooperation through the internet, which has enabled a considerable expansion of the commons principles.
more and more free software systems such as linux and wikipedia, are jointly developed and used according to strict rules.
knowledge goods such as recipes, maps, instructions and cutting patterns are managed collectively online.
the quality of common goods increased with the number of active users, the strict economic definition of commons does not apply.
modern varieties of the classic commons are establishing themselves in the form of jointly managed green spaces.

in view of the rapid destruction of many ecosystems within the framework of conventional forms of ownership, the common land principle is discussed as a possible form of administration for certain global goods such as the oceans, the atmosphere and the electromagnetic spectrum.
the containment of common goods in the form of privatization or nationalization is criticized, which leads to limitless overexploitation and often destruction (gridlock economy).
the commons principle is a paradigm shift in the logic of innovation.
the focus of the commons principle is on value instead of price.
the spread of the commons principle, for example in the form of open design, is a challenge for all actors in the classic market economy.
knowledge commons represent an important basis for many innovations.
the commons principle poses consequences for technology development: joint forms of usage place special demands on mobility or energy concepts.
the commons principles forms a building block for sustainable management.
the importance of the african countries as locations for innovative solutions is growing.
innovative products and services from the african continent are increasingly being presented in western media.
innovations from african countries are seen as intelligent, creative solutions for local societal needs under severe resource restrictions.

a sustainable up-and-coming shoe industry is emerging in ethiopia.

a new innovation pattern emerged in africa here that gains in importance in germany.

a lack of raw materials, debts and obsolescence make international high-tech companies rethink their innovation model.
products can no longer be provided with new functions and technical subtleties in a cost-intensive manner.

there is increased pressure on companies to act in a way that conserves ecology and is solution-oriented.
frugal innovations not only benefit companies in emerging countries, foreign companies also learn from frugal innovations and achieve competitive advantages.
technology groups such as siemens rely on frugal innovations in cooperation with local service providers (frugal engineering).
the point of frugal innovations is not just to develop cheap versions of high-tech products, but completely new ones.

the concept of frugal innovations is based on ingenuity through lack and has an impact on all levels of the innovation system.

the “art of omission” poses a major challenge for business models and organizational structures in western companies.
economic activities in tropical regions reached unprecedented proportions.
humans use more and more extreme economic areas, including the ocean floor and polar regions.
a large part of global economic activity will take place in extreme climatic areas particularly in the tropics and subtropics.

the shift of economic activities to extreme climatic areas is on the one hand stimulated by the emergence of numerous countries located in the tropics, on the other hand it enables these countries to emerge.
the spread of inexpensive air conditioning systems makes it easier to work in offices and systems under extreme climatic conditions.
regions that are favored for human activity are already largely developed.

tropical hygiene and diseases are becoming more and more enormous, especially in tropical regions.
energy consumption for air conditioning, corrosion-related deterioration in value and material input into the environment are increasing dramatically in importance.

in climatic regions with low biotic activity, such as the arctic, some ocean regions and on the sea floor, questions arise about the persistence and accumulation of humanly introduced materials and substances (including plastic, oil).
climate change and its consequences play a dominant role in research and innovation.
the effects of global socio-economic changes in terms of health, material and environmental issues are hardly exposed.

to deal with material requirements for buildings in extreme climatic rooms, climatic chambers in which different requirements for materials can be simulated and the recipes can be adapted to individual climatic zones, are used.

the global use of material goods is linked to product information systems (e.g. condition sensors, location) for the management of wear and tear and disposal.

citizens of the global middle class spend between 10 and 100 us dollars per capita on accommodation, health care, education and pensions. most of them have good working conditions and a sufficient income for consumption and leisure activities.
around a billion people in urban areas around the world belong to the middle class.
a large part of global economic growth (47%) and resource consumption is concentrated in the cities of developing and emerging countries.
what represents the most interesting market segment for management consultancies in the coming decades is a source of concern, but also of hope, especially for environmental policy.
the preferences of the new urban middle class from emerging countries adapted to the customs of western big city dwellers, so that the environmental pollution and co2 emissions increased.

the new global urban middle class is developing a growing interest in quality of life, but also in environmentally friendly technologies and products, and has the financial leeway for sustainable consumption patterns.
cities are seen as engines of economic growth, job creation and innovation - but also as causes of global warming and environmental pollution.

the urban middle classes are seen as the heart of the transformation to a green economy.

young people in western cities worldwide are reducing their meat consumption.
the consumer behavior of the middle class, especially in developing and emerging countries, enhanced the transformation towards a green economy.
with the support of research and innovation, old behavior patterns were replaced by new, sustainable and thus more effective behavior patterns.
urban areas with a high population density offer easier access to markets and a good basis for learning processes and marketing strategies for sustainable products, services and behavioral patterns.
in the areas of transport, infrastructure, energy and water supply, the development of sustainable technologies for cities save ecology and have great sales potential on the world market.
the concentration of humanity in urban and peri-urban regions represent an epochal trend in social change.
it is estimated that the world population will grow from around 8 billion today to 8.3 billion.
population growth goes hand in hand with redistribution: people are increasingly moving from rural areas to cities.
the redeployment and condensation of humanity gives the analysis of the social, economic and ecological significance of especially urban regions of paramount importance.
in the cultural and social sciences speak of a rediscovery of space.
the urbanization of rural or peripheral regions is driven by profound social, economic and psychological factors.
people are increasingly feeling the urge to want to emigrate.
people follow the charm of the city, which attracts them with the promise of a more diverse, safer, freer life.

new information and communication technologies and the expansion of transport infrastructures have made it easier to overcome distances and drastically increased the spatial self-sufficiency and mobility of workers.
regions and their spatial structure and design are still central to the economic power of nation states.
comparison, learning, copying and lateral thinking effects in metropolitan areas accelerate the cross-fertilization of previously disparate ideas, knowledge milieus and ethnic groups.
many innovations are only possible through spatial compression.
the creative classes, a mixture of scientists, designers, artists, consultants, advertisers, financiers who appreciate diversity want to see, touch, try out and debate.
urban regions are the innovation laboratories for the world economy.
urban milieus are globally mobile and volatile, but can't be tied permanently into stimulating spaces, surroundings, quarters and urban scenes.

urban regions are of global importance because they are integrated into supra-regional and global economic, social and ecological networks and impact structures through flows of people, ecology, goods and capital and globally intertwined supply, export and value chains.

there are a controversial discussion in research as to how one can promote urban innovation milieus without at the same time excluding other social milieus and creating metropolarities and regional peripheries.
the potential of the knowledge society unfolds particularly through mutual exchange in associations and networks. in this way, metropolitan areas enable synergies between different knowledge milieus.
60% of all people live in cities.
cities only occupy 2% of the earth's surface, but generate around 80% of global economic output, 75% of world energy consumption and around 70% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
cities are the stage on which many of the most important decisions on future trends such as the environment, sustainability or social cohesion will take place.
social, economic and technical solution strategies take effect in metropolitan areas and radiate widely to the hinterland of the cities and their globally stretched supply and export chains.
big cities are the local cause, but also a hope for solving global problems such as resource and environmental consumption or social quality of life.
urban governance and governability are among the most pressing problems of urbanization.
urban planning and research provide masses of empirical knowledge, but only a few generalizable recipes for urban management.
the challenges of city management includes the faster and spatially different development from the original planes of the urban planners.
laws and the development of infrastructures, such as transportation systems, are not able to keep pace with actual changes.
cities cannot adequately cope with environmental problems such as air pollution and its health effects, noise, land use, declining water quality, waste or heat islands.
deficits in legitimation, transparency and performance responsibility of governments and administrations, lack of experience with the efficiency, are the main challenges of cities.

low social cohesion due to overcrowded, dilapidated residential areas, districts with high unemployment and social marginalization, ethnic enclaves, law-free areas with crime and a pronounced shadow economy are the greatest problems of urban governability worldwide.
the right mix of different forms of political control, such as planning procedures, cooperation models and citizen participation, are the main challenges of cities.

gaps in the observation, analysis and evaluation of processes such as immigration or traffic flows in order to derive effectiveness and efficiency criteria for city management, are the main challenges of cities.
a lack of practical maturity of normative urban development concepts such as "compact city" or "new urbanism", are the main challenges of cities.
the development of civic and neighborly engagement in cities in order to be able to cope better with strong immigration flows and fluctuations in the population are too slow.
numerous disparate research results are available on multiple urban challenges, but they must be systematized to a far greater extent and examined for their transferability and generalizability.
in cities, economic and social innovations and trends are created, tested and adapted, and they can have an impact on their surroundings, national economies and global society.
environmental problems and social upheavals in the global economy are concentrated in cities.
success in researching and regulating economic, social and ecological challenges in cities are highly effective.
cities processes of political decision-making can be directly experienced.
the knowledge society plays an important role in cities, as it is what makes informed, knowledge-based decisions by social groups in cities possible in the first place.

the control of democratic political systems takes place in complex polycentric and cross-border constellations of actors and systems of rules, which leads to the development of new forms of negotiation of political decisions and a change in state tasks.
control of democratic political processes are often interpreted as the erosion of democracy's ability to act.
in view of the current financial and budget crisis as well as the slow handling of global challenges such as climate change or migration, a loss of legitimacy for democratic institutions is feared.
new institutions and patterns of interest mediation are emerging and expand the scope of nation states through new policy instruments such as cooperation networks.
the driver of the transformation of democratic statehood is the growing importance of supranational and transnational processes, organizations and movements from business and civil society.

the driver of the transformation of democratic statehood sets new norms across borders in political areas such as environmental or fiscal policy, organize solidarity, create legal frameworks and provide scientific expertise.

the driver of the transformation of democratic statehood is the growth of the multilevel integration of local, regional, national and supranational political systems and decision-making processes, which enable synergies, but can also result in fragmented, non-transparent and stagnant decisions.

the increase in political interest groups and neo-corporatist arrangements for compromise packages, for example in social or health policy, leads to the small-scale processing of distribution conflicts.

the neglect of future tasks beyond the daily or legislative policy horizon, the advance of initiatives for decentralization and regionalization of political powers as well for increased citizen participation and direct democracy reduce legitimacy of classical political institutions.
the increased political processes, their particularization, complexity and susceptibility forms a blockade in participation.
state-authorized private self-regulation of public services, for example in the transport and health sector, raise the effectiveness and legitimacy.
new forms of mediating politics open up new stages for social discourse about politics, but also contributes to the (mis-)information overload.
the increase in political advice at the intersection of foundations, lobbying and science, increase the knowledge-based nature, but also the time and coordination requirements of political processes.
to cope with societal challenges, innovative approaches build on the new forms of governance.
new methods such as foresight transition management are being used to coordinate transformative information.

economics and social sciences provide important impulses for strategies to improve the ability to act and make decisions as well as the legitimation of politics in complex and sometimes cross-border multi-level systems.
in view of the political science discourses on democracy and legitimation deficits in the european union (eu), decision-making processes arise, particularly in the context of the financial crisis.
the further course of european integration is increasingly characterized by uncertainties.

the european commission has designed three scenarios in a science-based foresight process that outline prototypical development paths of the eu and their implications for the most important policy areas and the geopolitical status of the eu up to 2050.
in view of the specific social and political challenges of the three scenarios described, actors in the innovation system should anticipate possible developments and adapt to them.
the science system continues to act as a driver for european integration in the future.
the economics and social sciences provide important innovative impulses for strategies to increase the legitimacy of eu institutions.
social networks on the internet enable citizens to discuss political events with many people around the world.
protests turned against political decisions - such as urban development project or even against political systems.
social networks serve as organizational platforms for political protests.
the uprising of oppressed populations, such as in egypt, can be distinguished from citizen activities that use the internet to demand more participation.
the systematic use of the internet by protest movements and the amalgamation of activities in the real world increases.
the oppression and lack of participation causes global protests, expressed on the internet.
online protests are picked up in the real world by the rest of the media in rapid speed.
in democratic societies, online organized protests shows a growing social need for participation and a considerable disruptive potential for political systems.
actors try to use the number of followers to gain the attention of the press and tv as the key to social pressure on politics.

there is a growing solidarity among citizens, as actions against right-wing extremism show and the movements are also fighting for the increasingly scarce resource of attention.
new forms of governance participation by citizens that develop beyond established structures are a central challenge of the future - especially for major innovations.
systematic research into new forms of communication emerges in this way can provide fundamental insights into future social developments.
50% of global resources are ethically and economically sustainable, coming from mining yesterday’s garbage dumps.
global migration has since decreased for first time in 15 years as domestic markets thrive.
leading global concrete manufacturers commitment to 100% renewable energy for all production, helping earth reach 1.5:1 consumption rate.
northern nations have even advocated increasing carbon emissions to accelerate the expansion of agricultural land and develop new areas for resource mining.
in canada and russia, large swathes of ice-prone land have become arable.
the extreme weather has had knock on effects in unexpected areas. seoul saw almost its entire electric vehicle fleet brought to a standstill due to the coldest winter on record.

fears are compounded following a disturbing article in the leading academic journal, nature, citing severe micronutrient deficiencies across large parts of the population due to over-reliance on synthetic food sources.
indonesia is the first country to execute fully circular processing on their waste and refuse.
sbts are the norm for building codes and urban design guidelines in both new and retrofit design based on the sbt materials assessment metric.

eu research and innovation programs support only eu missions and policies.
urban areas remain attractors for talent and hotspots of research and innovation.

policy, incentive schemes, and campaigns have created changes in food consumption patterns towards a sustainable society.

there is a global consensus that science, research and innovation are the key factors for a sustainable world and human wellbeing.
citizens engage in science and participate in research and innovation projects.

the globalised society has returned to more local structures. there is more emphasis than ever before on regional products.

community is sought on a small scale, because in the wake of the corona crisis the trend towards post-individualization has become attractive to a broader mass.
the fear of infection has spurred a retreat into the private sphere and the rediscovery of domesticity.
the neighbourhood help is a top priority, and there are fixed structures for helping each other in a crisis.
supplies are being shared or exchanged, special attention is paid to the old and weak.
instead of using public transport, people are more and more switching to bicycles or e-scooters.

the failure of global retail chains and mistrust of certain countries of origin are leading to a fundamental re-regionalisation of consumerism.

the regional economy functions completely autonomously.
new work trends are heading towards more flexicurity: flexibility in the workplace was made possible on a broad scale out of necessity has permanently changed working cultures.
home office is an essential part of every corporate culture, international companies arrange meetings in vr conferences, contracts are concluded via blockchain.
digital health applications are calculating the potential risk of personal business meetings in advance.
the world society has learned from the crisis and developing resilient, adaptive systems.

a sensible balance between online and offline markets has been achieved, a wise approach to globalised retail chains, a balance between local and global trade and direct trade platforms.
markets, regional producers and local online shops are booming.
society is moving away from mass consumption and a throwa-way mentality towards a healthier economic system.
health is now viewed more holistically: environment, city, politics, global community

the use of digital health apps has become a matter of course to share health data anonymously in real time.
